Vheadline
p2
VMelodious festival ragas
p3
sVnews
p4
VThe Soorya Music and Dance Festival 2008 got off to a grand start at Tagore Theatre, Thiruvananthapuram, with a Carnatic vocal concert by K.J. Yesudas. Coinciding with the International Music Day celebrations, Yesudas singing for the 31st year in a row for Soorya, enthralled the rasikas for almost four hours.His flawless rendition was rich in kalapramanam, bhava and diction. Yesudas opened his recital with a Sarasangi varnam.  He followed it with one of his guru, Chembai Vaidyanatha Bhagavathar&#8217;s favourites, &#8216;Vatapi Ganapathim Bhajeham&#8217; in Hamsadwani. The niraval was appropriately rendered at &#8216;Pranavaswaroopa vakrathundam.&#8217; S.R. Mahadeva Sarma picked up the swaras on his violin with finesse.Tyagaraja&#8217;s &#8216;Gurulekha Yeduvandi&#8217; in Gourimanohari was followed by an exposition of the raga Simhendramadhyamam. The kriti was Swati Tirunal&#8217;s &#8216;Rama Rama Guna Seema.&#8217; Tiruvarur Bhakthavalsalam&#8217;s deft strokes on the mridangam accompanied by Thripunithura Radhakrishnan on the ghatam during the taniavarthanam added lustre to the composition.&#8216;Harimuraleeravam,&#8217; &#8216;Shirdi Mera,&#8217; &#8216;Krishna Nee Begane Baro,&#8217; &#8216;Yenthe Kannanu Karuppuniram,&#8217; &#8216;Harivarasanam,&#8217; &#8216;Tripura Sundari&#8217; and &#8216;Narayaneeyam&#8217; were an outpouring of bhakti, karuna and sringara.T.M. Krishna began his vocal concert on the second day with Swati Tirunal&#8217;s &#8216;Janani Mamava&#8217; in Bhairavi, a Navaratri raga set to chappu talam. &#8216;Manavyala Kimchara&#8217; in Nalinakanti was noted for its rendering in a slow tempo.Elaborating on Sudhadhanyasi, Krishna rendered &#8216;Dalachina Varu.&#8217;  M.A Sundaresan sketched the raga&#8217;s bhava on his violin.The main piece of the evening was &#8216;Evari Matta&#8217; in Kambhoji. The kriti was set to Adi tala.  The thani, though subdued, was skilfully performed by K. Arun Prakash on the mridangam. Tampura artiste Rithik Raja gave vocal support.The other compositions of the day included &#8216;Vinatha Suthavahana&#8217; (Jayantasree), &#8216;Ka Vaa Vaa&#8217; (Varali), &#8216;Modijaya Seva&#8217; (Khamaj), a Balamuralikrishna tillana (Hamirkalyani) and a Bhadrachellam Ramdass&#8217; mangalam in Sankarabharanam.Playback singer Unnikrishnan started off his vocal recital with a Pantuvarali varnam and followed it with &#8216;Deva Deva Kalayamithe&#8217; in Mayamalavagoula.  &#8216;Bandureethi&#8217; in Hamsanadam and &#8216;Nadaloludai&#8217; in Kalyanavasantham came  next.Todi was the main raga. After delineating the raga, he rendered the kriti &#8216;Koluva Maragatha Kodandapani.&#8217;  A.L. Manjula Rajesh provided able support on the violin. The taniavarthanam saw Changanacherry B. Harikumar on the mridangam and Trivandrum Karthikeyan on the ghatam.Unnikrishnan concluded his two-and-a-half hour concert with a couple of thukkadas which included &#8216;Velane Vadivelane,&#8217; &#8216;Silaye Kaikondu Siva Rupamakunna&#8217; and mangalam.Sudha Ragunathan&#8217;s  three-hour concert began with a varnam in Mohanam. The kriti was Pattanam Subramania Iyer&#8217;s &#8216;Ninnu Vina.&#8217;As an invocation to Ganesha, she rendered Ambujam Krishna&#8217;s &#8216;Varanamukhane Vaa&#8217; in Natta set to Adi tala. This kriti was preceded by a virutham beginning with &#8216;Palum telithenum.&#8217; Subbaraya Sastri&#8217;s &#8216;Janani Amba Janani&#8217; in Ritigoula,  set to Misra chappu talam, was dedicated to all the great teachers of Carnatic music.After a brief ragavistaram, Sudha Ragunathan rendered Ramnad Srinivasa Iyengar&#8217;s &#8216;Parama pavana&#8217; in Poorvikalyani. The kriti was noted for its smooth swarasancharam.The highlight of the day was the famous Tyagaraja composition &#8216;Pakkala nila batti&#8217; in Kharaharapriya. The intricacies of the raga were portrayed in her pleasing voice to the accompaniment of Kumbakonam M.R. Gopinath&#8217;s violin.The taniavarthanam was performed by R. Raman on the mridangam and Palladam R. Ravi on the morsing. The thukkadas comprised &#8216;Marukelara O Raghava, Visweswara Darsana Karo&#8217; and a thillana.Bombay Jayasree&#8217;s kutcheri on the final day, was noted for its bhava, laya and gamagaprayogas. Beginning with a varnam in Devagandhari, she moved on to &#8216;Sambho Mahadeva&#8217; in Pantuvarali. G. N. Balasubramaniam&#8217;s &#8216;Nee Padamegati&#8217; in Nalinakanti was set to Roopaka tala. She gave a different feel to Tyagaraja&#8217;s popular kriti &#8216;Mokshamogaladhe&#8217; in Saramati, beginning initially with the high octave &#8216;Sakshatkarini&#8217; in the anupallavi.However, the attraction of Bombay Jayasree&#8217;s concert was a ragam tanam pallavi in Sanmughapriya.  Violinist Embar S. Kannan sketched beautifully the nuances of the raga. The taniavarthanam stood out for the smooth and dexterous exchanges between Poomkulam Subramaniam on the mridangam and S. Karthick on the ghatam.Bombay Jayasree concluded her three-and-a-half hour concert with a Hindi bhajan, a soulful singing of &#8216;Jaya Jaya Deva Hare,&#8217; and a tillana in Behag.
